<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>Knowledge Selection Principle.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>Social Selection Principle.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>Knowledge selection is a kind of social selection.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>The interests of readers determine the selection of summaries.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>Suitable Summarizer.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>Relativity Principle.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>Separation Principle.</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>Moderate Principle.</a>
<a name="8">[8]</a> <a href="#8" id=8>The person who shares the represented knowledge and the knowledge for representation is suitable for summarization.</a>
<a name="9">[9]</a> <a href="#9" id=9>Openness Principle.</a>
<a name="10">[10]</a> <a href="#10" id=10>The suitable summarizer for summarizing a representation is rendered by the social network of its writers and readers.</a>
<a name="11">[11]</a> <a href="#11" id=11>The following lemmas can be derived from the knowledge selection principle:</a>
<a name="12">[12]</a> <a href="#12" id=12>The inexact principle and the relativity principle indicate the following principles:</a>
<a name="13">[13]</a> <a href="#13" id=13>Dynamicity Principle.</a>
<a name="14">[14]</a> <a href="#14" id=14>The above principle means that even people sharing the represented knowledge may not be the suitable person for summarizing the representation because they may not have the knowledge of representation.</a>
<a name="15">[15]</a> <a href="#15" id=15>This is because authors have the knowledge for representation and the knowledge to be represented.</a>
<a name="16">[16]</a> <a href="#16" id=16>(5) Transforming summarizations into the problem of searching suitable persons or summaries in the social networks of authors, readers, summarizers, representations and links.</a>
<a name="17">[17]</a> <a href="#17" id=17>This requests a summarizer to collect and analyze readers' interests according to their reading behaviors and attitudes to summaries.</a>
<a name="18">[18]</a> <a href="#18" id=18>The following are principles of selecting a suitable summarizer.</a>
<a name="19">[19]</a> <a href="#19" id=19>(2) Knowledge for representation (e.g., grammars and idioms) and knowledge to be represented (e.g., scientific knowledge) are separated.</a>
<a name="20">[20]</a> <a href="#20" id=20>(2) Adapting to readers' interests.</a>
<a name="21">[21]</a> <a href="#21" id=21>This is because the establishment of rich social relations indicates common individual characteristics and social characteristics.</a>
<a name="22">[22]</a> <a href="#22" id=22>The problem of designing a suitable summarizer can be transformed into the problem of searching a suitable summarizer in cyberspace.</a>
<a name="23">[23]</a> <a href="#23" id=23>The satisfied summaries of a representation vary with time.</a>
<a name="24">[24]</a> <a href="#24" id=24>A friend of author may not be the suitable summarizer.</a>
<a name="25">[25]</a> <a href="#25" id=25>A good summarizer should know its potential readers.</a>
<a name="26">[26]</a> <a href="#26" id=26>The moderate principle indicates that the best summary does not exist.</a>
